1 3. The department of commerce shall allocate funding appropriated in this section as
2 follows:
3 a. $10,000,000 for communities with a population of fewer than 5,000 individuals;
4 b. $20,000,000 for communities with a population of 5,001 to 20,000 individuals;
5 c. $15,000,000 for communities with a population of more than 20,000 individuals;
6 and
7 d. $5,000,000 for rural metropolitan areas located within 20 miles of the city center
8 of a community of more than 20,000 individuals.
9 4. The maximum grant award for a community with more than 20,000 individuals is
10 $1,500,000.
11 5. If all funding appropriated in this section is not committed or expended by
12 December 31, 2026, the department of commerce may award any remaining funds to
13 viable projects regardless of community size or location.
14 6. The department of commerce may spend the funds appropriated in this section only to
15 the extent matching funds have been secured from nonstate sources on a
16 dollar-for-dollar basis. The matching funds must be derived equally from funds
17 provided by a political subdivision, funds provided from local developers, and private
18 funds from within the community applying for grant funding. The private funds from
19 within the community may be from a local development corporation, donations, or
20 in-kind contributions.
21 7. The department of commerce shall provide a report to the legislative management and
22 the governor by June 30, 2026, regarding the status of the program, including
23 expenditures to date, the number of housing units supported, communities applying for
24 grants, and matching funds raised by political subdivisions, local developers, and
25 communities.
26 SECTION 2. EMERGENCY. This Act is declared to be an emergency measure.
